<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">24053525</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2016</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>22</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2018</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>02</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1715-5320</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>38</Volume><Issue>11</Issue><PubDate><Year>2013</Year><Month>Nov</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Applied physiology, nutrition, and metabolism = Physiologie appliquee, nutrition et metabolisme</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Appl Physiol Nutr Metab</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effects of resistance training associated with whey protein supplementation on liver and kidney biomarkers in rats.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1166</StartPage><EndPage>1169</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1166-9</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1139/apnm-2013-0004</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The aim of this study was to investigate the impact of whey protein (WP) supplementation and resistance training (RT) on liver and kidney biomarkers. The sedentary + WP group showed higher levels of plasma liver and kidney dysfunction markers compared with the other groups. In addition, WP supplementation associated with RT resulted in physiologic cardiac hypertrophy. WP supplementation without RT affected liver and kidney function.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Nunes</LastName><ForeName>Ramiro</ForeName><Initials>R</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Nutrition, Universidade Federal de Ci&#xea;ncias da Sa&#xfa;de de Porto Alegre, Sarmento Leite Street, 245/611&#x2009;-&#x2009;Porto Alegre&#x2009;-&#x2009;RS CEP: 90050-170, Brazil.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Silva</LastName><ForeName>Priscila</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials></Author><Author Val